06:26.440 --> 06:33.700
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Ray Bradbury is an internationally known
author who's managed to attract readers outside the field of science fiction and

06:33.700 --> 06:40.740
fantasy. In fact, he's one of the few writers of science fiction and fantasy
whose name is almost instantly recognizable outside the field. He's also written

06:40.740 --> 06:48.700
so-called mainstream, a regular fiction ever since he began publishing early in
the 1940s. Dandelion Wine, a poetic novel about a boy growing up in a small

06:48.700 --> 06:55.640
Midwestern town, is one example of his non-science fiction output. We asked him
how he broke out of the restricted field of science fiction and gained such

06:55.640 --> 07:06.260
widespread acceptance for all of his fiction with all types of readers. Well,
you just automatically think about it for a lifetime. I always dreamt of being,

07:06.420 --> 07:17.220
number one, a writer, not a writer of science fiction or a writer of fantasy,
but a writer, period. I had huge heroes that I looked up to in the world, people

07:17.220 --> 07:27.660
like Shakespeare and a lot of the great poets, Emily Dickinson and Robert Frost
when I was in my teens. And then as I got older and began to see the world of

07:27.660 --> 07:37.380
the theater around me more, I wanted to do theater work. I loved motion
pictures. I knew that eventually I wanted to do some films. So my interests were

07:37.380 --> 07:47.100
always very Catholic, very broad, and it was only a matter of time before I
would experiment with each of these things. And at the same time I was writing

07:47.100 --> 07:57.680
and having my first success of selling stories to weird tales, I was beginning
to write short stories in the larger fields. Stories about racial relationships

07:57.680 --> 08:08.000
or stories about travel inside America, a little bit of everything I was
experimenting with. Bradbury said he was about 25 when he first began publishing

08:08.000 --> 08:18.120
stories that were not science fiction or fantasy. A friend of mine called me on
the phone, said he was going to Mexico to travel for two months. Did I want to

08:18.120 --> 08:29.480
come along? Well, I said, I can't. I don't have any money. I was still only
making around $20 a week selling stories to weird tales. I usually sold six

08:29.480 --> 08:38.800
stories to weird tales every year, which gave me around $120 for the whole year.
And then I sold an occasional murder mystery and a few science fiction stories.

08:38.900 --> 08:50.800
So my income at the time was around $2,500 a year if I was lucky. And he said,
oh, you're such a coward. He said, here, the war is over. War has been over in

08:50.800 --> 09:00.480
Europe a month or so. You should travel. And you're afraid to send out your
short stories. You're afraid of being rejected. I know you've got a lot of

09:00.480 --> 09:12.700
excellent, broad, literary, middle stream fictions. I actually retype them and
send them out. So by God, he egged me on. And I got three short stories out of

09:12.700 --> 09:23.560
my files. I retyped them, put an assumed name on each one, William Elliott. I
mailed them off without an agent, without any representation, with not even a

09:23.560 --> 09:34.200
letter from myself to the editors. And one story to Charm, one story to
Mademoiselle, and another one to Collier's. Bradbury got a big surprise and a

09:34.200 --> 09:45.580
big paycheck after sending those three stories in. Well, all three stories sold
within three days of each other. One story sold on August 19th to Charm. On the

09:45.580 --> 09:55.160
20th, one to Mademoiselle. And on my birthday, the 22nd of August, I sold my
first short story to Collier's. So all of a sudden, I had an aggregate of $1

09:55.160 --> 10:09.520
,000, which arrived in the mail. Well, $1,000 back in 1945 would be like getting
$15,000 in the mail today. I was out of my head. I couldn't believe it. So with

10:09.520 --> 10:18.840
that money, I picked up and went to Mexico with him for six weeks, where I had a
whole series of adventures that scared the hell out of me and caused me to write

10:18.840 --> 10:28.180
some of my best weird stories when I came home. So that's the way I made the
transition, because someone called me a coward and dared me to send my stories

10:28.180 --> 10:31.700
out. On our next show, we'll have more with Ray Bradbury.

