12:09.140 --> 12:16.920
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. . Ray Bradbury's The Martian Chronicles is
one of the best-known science fiction books produced in this country. Its poetic

12:16.920 --> 12:23.760
style, its treatment of mankind's present problems, and its vision of man's
future make it a book admired not only by regular readers of science fiction,

12:23.800 --> 12:31.300
but by anyone who reads it all. . The book is really a collection of related
short stories concerning man's colonization of Mars. We asked Bradbury if he

12:31.300 --> 12:34.840
wrote each story with the entire volume in mind. .

12:40.740 --> 12:53.440
. . I went to New York City in June of 1949. My wife was pregnant with our first
child. We had about $80 in the bank. And I took the Greyhound bus to New York,

12:53.480 --> 12:55.320
and I took all my short stories with me.

12:59.160 --> 13:29.760
. . . . . Well, I had meetings with various people at Simon & Schuster and
Doubleday, and they all said, . .

13:29.760 --> 13:40.680
. of hanging them all together. It seems to me there's a common thread. I said,
oh my God. You know, years ago I made notes about doing a series of chronicles

13:40.680 --> 13:49.560
and then threw the notes somewhere and forgot about them. So my subconscious
must have remembered and along through the years was putting these beads on a

13:49.560 --> 14:01.220
single thread. I went back to the YMCA that night, sat in my underwear. It was a
hot, hot summer evening, terribly humid, and finished typing out an outline of a

14:01.220 --> 14:10.220
book which I called The Martian Chronicles, which I then took to Doubleday the
next day and they promptly bought the novel plus the illustrated man, a

14:10.220 --> 14:22.400
collection of stories. And I left New York City with, again, a fabulous $1,000,
$500 for each book. The stories are not scientifically accurate. Man can breathe

14:22.400 --> 14:29.520
the Martian atmosphere unaided, for example, but they're not meant to be. They
have to be read symbolically. At a deep, unconscious level which is triggered by

14:29.520 --> 14:37.400
Bradbury's poetic way of writing. There is an order to the 26 stories that make
up The Martian Chronicles. The final one is entitled The Million Year Picnic and

14:37.400 --> 14:49.340
we asked Bradbury why he put that one last. It seemed a proper place to put it.
It seemed a culmination of all the stories and that my job in looking at all my

14:49.340 --> 14:58.580
stories was to guess where to place each. And while some of them it was very
easy, I did a whole series of stories of first encounters on Mars with various

14:58.580 --> 15:10.060
expeditions. So I knew those automatically had to be up front along with an
imaginary encounter in Illa where a woman dreams an invasion of Mars. We never

15:10.060 --> 15:19.260
see the invasion itself of the Earth men, but we know that secretly it must be
there somewhere and that real people got killed by the jealous husband. And then

15:19.260 --> 15:30.300
you go along through all the other encounters and what happens to Mars as a
result of the invasion by Earth people. And ending with all of your final beats

15:30.300 --> 15:42.000
and a brief return to Earth for there will come soft rains and then the million
-year picnic at the end. It all fell together in roughly two hours in my head at

15:42.000 --> 15:51.900
the typewriter that night at the YMCA. In 1980, NBC produced a major six-hour
dramatization of the Martian Chronicles. We asked Bradbury if he was happy with

15:51.900 --> 16:04.940
it. I most certainly was not. It was one of the most boring shows ever put on
television. And it's a great shame. Obviously, no one enjoyed doing it. And the

16:04.940 --> 16:13.660
director obviously didn't enjoy it, which is a great shame because he should
have got out of bed every morning and said, let's have a ball, let's play, let's

16:13.660 --> 16:22.740
jump up and down and scream and yell and get something out of this material. But
he obviously didn't do that. We'll have more with Ray Bradbury on our next show.

